Definition 5.1. We say that two pairs $(G,\,\overline{\omega})$ and $(G^{\prime},\,\overline{\omega}^{\prime})$ are categorically Morita equivalent and write $(G,\,\overline{\omega})\thickapprox(G^{\prime},\,\overline{\omega}^{\prime})$ if the tensor categories $Vec(G,\,\omega)$ and $Vec(G^{\prime},\,\omega^{\prime})$, are weakly Morita equivalent.
Definition 3.1 An object $M$ of $\cal A$ is called a regular object if $M$ is $U_{i}$-regular for any $i\in I$.
Definition 1.1 Let $U$ and $M$ be objects of a category $\cal A$. Then $M$ is called $U$-regular if and only if any morphism $f:U\rightarrow M$ has a generalized inverse.
Definition 6.1. [3] Let $X$ be a flow. Let $A$ and $B$ be two subsets of $X^{0}$. One says that $A$ is surrounded by $B$ (in $X$) if for any $\alpha\in A$, either $\alpha\in B$ or there exists execution paths $\gamma_{1}$ and $\gamma_{2}$ of $\mathbb{P}X$ such that $s(\gamma_{1})\in B$, $t(\gamma_{1})=s(\gamma_{2})=\alpha$ and $t(\gamma_{2})\in B$. We denote this situation by $A\lll B$.
Definition 7.2. [11] The homotopy pushout of the diagram of flows $\xymatrix{A\ar@{->}[r]^{-}{}\ar@{->}[d]&B\\ C&}$ is the colimit of the diagram of flows $\xymatrix{&A\otimes\Delta^{0}\ar@{->}[d]\ar@{->}[r]^{-}{}&B\\ A\otimes\Delta^{0}\ar@{->}[d]\ar@{->}[r]^{-}{}&A\otimes\Delta^{1}&\\ C&&}$
Definition 3.2. [3] A flow $X$ consists of a topological space $\mathbb{P}X$, a discrete space $X^{0}$, two continuous maps $s$ and $t$ from $\mathbb{P}X$ to $X^{0}$ and a continuous and associative map $*:\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{P}X\times\mathbb{P}X;t(x)=s(y)\}\longrightarrow\mathbb{P}X$ such that $s(x*y)=s(x)$ and $t(x*y)=t(y)$. A morphism of flows $f:X\longrightarrow Y$ consists of a set map $f^{0}:X^{0}\longrightarrow Y^{0}$ together with a continuous map $\mathbb{P}f:\mathbb{P}X\longrightarrow\mathbb{P}Y$ such that $f(s(x))=s(f(x))$, $f(t(x))=t(f(x))$ and $f(x*y)=f(x)*f(y)$. The corresponding category will be denoted by ${\rm{\mathbf{Flow}}}$.
Definition 4.6. The homotopy branching space $\operatorname{ho\mathbb{P}}^{-}X$ of a flow $X$ is by definition the topological space $\mathbb{P}^{-}Q(X)$.
Definition 6.9. [5] A morphism of flows $f:X\longrightarrow Y$ is a $2$-dihomotopy equivalence if and only if the following conditions are satisfied : (1) The morphism of flows $f:X\longrightarrow Y\!\restriction_{f(X^{0})}$ is a weak S-homotopy equivalence of flows. In particular, the set map $f^{0}:X^{0}\longrightarrow Y^{0}$ is one-to-one. (2) For $\alpha\in Y^{0}\backslash f(X^{0})$, the topological spaces $\operatorname{ho\mathbb{P}}^{-}_{\alpha}Y$ and $\operatorname{ho\mathbb{P}}^{+}_{\alpha}Y$ are weakly contractible. (3) $Y^{0}\lll f(X^{0})$. The class of $2$-dihomotopy equivalences is denoted by $\mathcal{ST}_{2}$.
Definition 2.2. [12, 11] A model structure on a category $\mathcal{C}$ is three subcategories of $Map(\mathcal{C})$ called weak equivalences, cofibrations, and fibrations, and two functorial factorizations $(\alpha,\beta)$ and $(\gamma,\delta)$ satisfying the following properties : (1) (2-out-of-3) If $f$ and $g$ are morphisms of $\mathcal{C}$ such that $g\circ f$ is defined and two of $f$, $g$ and $g\circ f$ are weak equivalences, then so is the third. (2) (Retracts) If $f$ and $g$ are morphisms of $\mathcal{C}$ such that $f$ is a retract of $g$ and $g$ is a weak equivalence, cofibration, or fibration, then so is $f$. (3) (Lifting) Define a map to be a trivial cofibration if it is both a cofibration and a weak equivalence. Similarly, define a map to be a trivial fibration if it is both a fibration and a weak equivalence. Then trivial cofibrations have the LLP with respect to fibrations, and cofibrations have the LLP with respect to trivial fibrations. (4) (Factorization) For any morphism $f$, $\alpha(f)$ is a cofibration, $\beta(f)$ a trivial fibration, $\gamma(f)$ is a trivial cofibration , and $\delta(f)$ is a fibration.
Definition 2.5. [12, 11] An object $X$ of a model category $\mathcal{C}$ is cofibrant (resp. fibrant) if and only if the canonical morphism $\varnothing\longrightarrow X$ from the initial object of $\mathcal{C}$ to $X$ (resp. the canonical morphism $X\longrightarrow\mathbf{1}$ from $X$ to the final object $\mathbf{1}$) is a cofibration (resp. a fibration).
Definition 6.3. [3] A morphism of flows $f:X\longrightarrow Y$ is a $0$-dihomotopy equivalence if and only if the following conditions are satisfied : (1) The morphism of flows $f:X\longrightarrow Y\!\restriction_{f(X^{0})}$ is a weak S-homotopy equivalence of flows. In particular, the set map $f^{0}:X^{0}\longrightarrow Y^{0}$ is one-to-one. (2) For $\alpha\in Y^{0}\backslash f(X^{0})$, the topological spaces $\mathbb{P}^{-}_{\alpha}Y$ and $\mathbb{P}^{+}_{\alpha}Y$ are singletons. (3) $Y^{0}\lll f(X^{0})$. The class of $0$-dihomotopy equivalences is denoted by $\mathcal{ST}_{0}$.
Definition 3.5. [5] An $I^{gl}_{+}$-cell complex is a flow $X$ such that the canonical morphism of flows $\varnothing\longrightarrow X$ from the initial object of ${\rm{\mathbf{Flow}}}$ to $X$ is a transfinite composition of pushouts of elements of $I^{gl}_{+}$. The full and faithful subcategory of ${\rm{\mathbf{Flow}}}$ whose objects are the $I^{gl}_{+}$-cell complexes will be denoted by ${I^{gl}_{+}\rm{\mathbf{cell}}}$.
Definition 2.3. [12, 11] A model category is a complete and cocomplete category $\mathcal{C}$ together with a model structure on $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 6.12. [5] A morphism of flows $f:X\longrightarrow Y$ is a $3$-dihomotopy equivalence if the following conditions are satisfied : (1) $A\subset X^{0}$ is essential if and only if $f(A)\subset Y^{0}$ is essential (2) for any essential $A\subset X^{0}$ there exists an essential subset $B\subset A$ such that the restriction $f:X\!\restriction_{B}\longrightarrow Y\!\restriction_{f(B)}$ is a weak S-homotopy equivalence. The class of $3$-dihomotopy equivalences is denoted by $\mathcal{ST}_{3}$.
Definition 2.1. [12, 11] Let $i:A\longrightarrow B$ and $p:X\longrightarrow Y$ be maps in a category $\mathcal{C}$. Then $i$ has the left lifting property (LLP) with respect to $p$ (or $p$ has the right lifting property (RLP) with respect to $i$) if for any commutative square $\xymatrix{A\ar@{->}[d]_{i}\ar@{->}[r]^{-}{\alpha}&X\ar@{->}[d]_{p}\\ B\ar@{-->}[ru]^{g}\ar@{->}[r]^{-}{\beta}&Y}$ there exists $g$ making both triangles commutative.
Definition 6.11. [5] Let $X$ be a flow. Then a subset $A$ of $X^{0}$ is essential if $X^{0}\lll A$ and if for any $\alpha\notin A$, both topological spaces $\operatorname{ho\mathbb{P}}^{-}_{\alpha}X$ and $\operatorname{ho\mathbb{P}}^{+}_{\alpha}X$ are weakly contractible.
Definition 5.2. [5] Let $X$ be a flow. The topological space $\mathbb{P}^{+}X$ is called the merging space of the flow $X$.
Definition 7.4. [4] Let $f:X\longrightarrow Y$ be a morphism of flows. The cone $Cf$ of $f$ is the homotopy pushout in the category of flows $\xymatrix{X\ar@{->}[r]^{-}{f}\ar@{->}[d]&Y\ar@{->}[d]\\ \textbf{1}\ar@{->}[r]^{-}{}&Cf}$ where 1 is the terminal flow.
Definition 6.2. [3] Let $X$ be a flow. Let $A$ be a subset of $X^{0}$. Then the restriction $X\!\restriction_{A}$ of $X$ over $A$ is the unique flow such that $\left(X\!\restriction_{A}\right)^{0}=A$ and $\mathbb{P}\left(X\!\restriction_{A}\right)=\bigsqcup_{\left(\alpha,\beta\right% )\in A\times A}\mathbb{P}_{\alpha,\beta}X$ equipped with the topology induced by the one of $\mathbb{P}X$.
Definition 3.3. [3] Let $Z$ be a topological space. Then the globe of $Z$ is the flow ${\rm{Glob}}(Z)$ defined as follows: ${\rm{Glob}}(Z)^{0}=\{0,1\}$, $\mathbb{P}{\rm{Glob}}(Z)=Z$, $s=0$, $t=1$ and the composition law is trivial.
Definition 5.4. [5] The homotopy merging space $\operatorname{ho\mathbb{P}}^{+}X$ of a flow $X$ is by definition the topological space $\mathbb{P}^{+}Q(X)$.
Definition 7.1. [15, 12, 11] x A simplicial model category is a model category $\mathcal{C}$ together with a simplicial set $\operatorname{Map}(X,Y)$ for any object $X$ and $Y$ of $\mathcal{C}$ satisfying the following axioms: (1) the set $\operatorname{Map}(X,Y)_{0}$ is canonically isomorphic to $\mathcal{C}(X,Y)$ (2) for any object $X$, $Y$ and $Z$, there is a morphism of simplicial sets $\operatorname{Map}(Y,Z)\times\operatorname{Map}(X,Y)\longrightarrow% \operatorname{Map}(X,Z)$ which is associative (3) for any object $X$ of $\mathcal{C}$ and any simplicial set $K$, there exists an object $X\otimes K$ of $\mathcal{C}$ such that there exists a natural isomorphism of simplicial sets $\operatorname{Map}(X\otimes K,Y)\cong\operatorname{Map}(K,\operatorname{Map}(X% ,Y))$ (4) for any object $X$ of $\mathcal{C}$ and any simplicial set $K$, there exists an object $X^{K}$ such that there exists a natural isomorphism of simplicial sets $\operatorname{Map}(X,Y^{K})\cong\operatorname{Map}(K,\operatorname{Map}(X,Y))$ (5) for any cofibration $i:A\longrightarrow B$ and any fibration $p:X\longrightarrow Y$ of $\mathcal{C}$, the morphism of simplicial sets $Q(i,p):\operatorname{Map}(B,X)\longrightarrow\operatorname{Map}(A,X)\times_{% \operatorname{Map}(A,Y)}\operatorname{Map}(B,Y)$ is a fibration of simplicial sets. Moreover if either $i$ or $p$ is trivial, then the fibration $Q(i,p)$ is trivial as well.
Definition 4.2. [3, 5] Let $X$ be a flow. The topological space $\mathbb{P}^{-}X$ is called the branching space of the flow $X$.
Definition 7.6. [4] Let $X$ be a flow. Then the $(n+1)$st branching homology group $H_{n+1}^{-}(X)$ is defined as the $n$st homology group of the augmented simplicial set $\mathcal{N}^{-}_{*}(X)$ defined as follows: (1) $\mathcal{N}^{-}_{n}(X)=S_{n}(\operatorname{ho\mathbb{P}}^{-}X)$ for $n\geqslant 0$ (2) $\mathcal{N}^{-}_{-1}(X)=X^{0}$ (3) the augmentation map $\epsilon:S_{0}(\operatorname{ho\mathbb{P}}^{-}X)\longrightarrow X^{0}$ is induced by the mapping $\gamma\mapsto s(\gamma)$ from $\operatorname{ho\mathbb{P}}^{-}X=S_{0}(\operatorname{ho\mathbb{P}}^{-}X)$ to $X^{0}$.
Definition 6.5. [5] A morphism of flows $f:X\longrightarrow Y$ is a $1$-dihomotopy equivalence if and only if the following conditions are satisfied : (1) The morphism of flows $f:X\longrightarrow Y\!\restriction_{f(X^{0})}$ is a weak S-homotopy equivalence of flows. In particular, the set map $f^{0}:X^{0}\longrightarrow Y^{0}$ is one-to-one. (2) For $\alpha\in Y^{0}\backslash f(X^{0})$, the topological spaces $\mathbb{P}^{-}_{\alpha}Y$ and $\mathbb{P}^{+}_{\alpha}Y$ are weakly contractible. (3) $Y^{0}\lll f(X^{0})$. The class of $1$-dihomotopy equivalences is denoted by $\mathcal{ST}_{1}$.
Definition 3.6. A Dirac structure of the omni-Lie $2$-algebra $(\mathfrak{gl}(\mathbb{V})\oplus\mathbb{V},\left\langle\cdot,\cdot\right% \rangle,\left\llbracket\cdot,\cdot\right\rrbracket)$ is a maximal isotropic $2$-sub-vector space, i.e. $\mathbb{L}=\mathbb{L}^{\perp}$, which is closed under the bracket operation $\left\llbracket\cdot,\cdot\right\rrbracket$.
Definition 5.4. A Dirac structure of the omni-Lie $2$-algebra $\mathfrak{gl}(\mathbb{V})\oplus_{\mu}\mathbb{V}$ is a maximal isotropic $2$-sub-vector space (w.r.t. $\langle\cdot,\cdot\rangle_{\mu}$) closed under the bracket operation $\left\llbracket\cdot,\cdot\right\rrbracket_{\mu}$.
Definition 2.1. [1] A $2$-vector space is a category in the category $\mathrm{Vect}$.
Definition 5.1. [1] Given Lie $2$-algebras $C$ and $C^{\prime}$, a Lie $2$-algebra morphism $\mu:C\longrightarrow C^{\prime}$ consists of: $\bullet$ a linear functor $(\mu_{0},\mu_{1})$ from the underlying $2$-vector space of $C$ to that of $C^{\prime}$, and $\bullet$ a skew-symmetric bilinear natural transformation $\mu_{2}(u,v):\mu_{0}[u,v]\longrightarrow[\mu_{0}(u),\mu_{0}(v)]$ such that the following diagram commutes: $\xymatrix{\mu_{0}[[u,v],w]\ar[d]_{\mu_{2}([u,v],w)}\ar[rr]^{\mu_{0}J_{u,v,w}% \quad\qquad\quad}&&\mu_{0}[u,[v,w]]+\mu_{0}[v,[w,u]]\ar[d]^{\mu_{2}(u,[v,w])+% \mu_{2}(v,[w,u])}\\ ~{}[\mu_{0}[u,v],\mu_{0}(w)]\ar[d]_{[\mu_{2}(u,v),id_{\mu_{0}(w)}]}&&[\mu_{0}(% u),\mu_{0}[v,w]]+[\mu_{0}(v),\mu_{0}[w,u]]\ar[d]^{[id_{\mu_{0}(u)},\mu_{2}(v,w% )]+[id_{\mu_{0}(v)},\mu_{2}(w,u)]}\\ ~{}[[\mu_{0}(u),\mu_{0}(v)],\mu_{0}(w)]\ar[rr]^{J\qquad\quad}&&[\mu_{0}(u),[% \mu_{0}(v),\mu_{0}(w)]]+[\mu_{0}(v),[\mu_{0}(w),\mu_{0}(u)]].}$ We call $\mu$ strict if $\mu_{2}=0$. We call $\mu$ an isomorphism if it induces an isomorphism of the underlying $2$-vector spaces.
Definition 3.3. The triple $(\mathfrak{gl}(\mathbb{V})\oplus\mathbb{V},\left\langle\cdot,\cdot\right% \rangle,\left\llbracket\cdot,\cdot\right\rrbracket)$ is called the omni-Lie $2$-algebra associated to the $2$-vector space $\mathbb{V}$, where $\left\langle\cdot,\cdot\right\rangle$ is the symmetric bilinear functor given by (8) and $\left\llbracket\cdot,\cdot\right\rrbracket$ is the skew-symmetric bilinear functor given by (13). We simply denote the omni-Lie $2$-algebra by $\mathfrak{gl}(\mathbb{V})\oplus\mathbb{V}$.
Definition 4.1. The normalizer of a $2$-sub-vector space $\mathbb{K}\subset\mathfrak{gl}(\mathbb{V})\oplus\mathbb{V}$ is composed of all the elements $N\in\mathfrak{gl}(\mathbb{V})$ such that $\{N,\mathbb{K}\}\subset\mathbb{K},$ with $\{\cdot,\cdot\}$ defined in (15).
Definition 2.4. An $L_{\infty}$-algebra is a graded vector space $L=L_{0}\oplus L_{1}\oplus\cdots$ equipped with a system $\{l_{k}|~{}1\leq k<\infty\}$ of linear maps $l_{k}:\wedge^{k}L\longrightarrow L$ with degree2 the exterior powers are interpreted in the graded sense. $\deg(l_{k})=k-2$, such that the following relation with Koszul sign “Ksgn” is satisfied for all $n\geq 0$: $\sum_{i+j=n+1}(-1)^{i(j-1)}\sum_{\sigma}\mathrm{sgn}(\sigma)\mathrm{Ksgn}(% \sigma)l_{j}(l_{i}(x_{\sigma(1)},\cdots,x_{\sigma(i)}),x_{\sigma(i+1)},\cdots,% x_{\sigma(n)})=0.$ The summation in this equation is taken over all $(i,n-i)$-unshuffles with $1\leq i\leq n-1$.
Definition 2.2. A Lie $2$-algebra is a $2$-vector space $C$ equipped with $\bullet$ a skew-symmetric bilinear functor, the bracket, $[\cdot,\cdot]:C\times C\longrightarrow C$, $\bullet$ a skew-symmetric trilinear natural isomorphism, the Jacobiator, $J_{x,y,z}:[[x,y],z]\longrightarrow[x,[y,z]]+[[x,z],y],$ such that the following Jacobiator identity is satisfied, $\displaystyle J_{[w,x],y,z}([J_{w,x,z},y]+1)(J_{w,[x,z],y}+J_{[w,z],x,y}+J_{w,% x,[y,z]})$ $\displaystyle=[J_{w,x,y},z](J_{[w,y],x,z}+J_{w,[x,y],z})([J_{w,y,z},x]+1)([w,J% _{x,y,z}]+1).$
Definition 5.2. The triple $(\mathfrak{gl}(\mathbb{V})\oplus\mathbb{V},\left\llbracket\cdot,\cdot\right% \rrbracket_{\mu},\left\langle\cdot,\cdot\right\rangle_{\mu})$ is called a $\mu$-twisted omni-Lie $2$-algebra. We simply denote it by $\mathfrak{gl}(\mathbb{V})\oplus_{\mu}\mathbb{V}$.
